answers.body_markdown:
There is nothing wrong with `EOFException` 

&gt; Signals that an end of file or end of stream has been reached unexpectedly during input. 

In the example you have provided
```
Student x = (Student) in.readObject();
if(x != null)   
```
`readObject` will not return null when end of file is reached it throws `EOFException`, so if there is a file with the following content:
```
StudentA
StudentB
```
`StudentA` and `StudentB` will be added to `objectsList`, but on the third execution `readObject()` will throw `EOFException`

The main issue here is how you handle this exception, try something like this:
```
while(cont){
 try{
   Object x = (Object) in.readObject();
 } catch (EOFException e) {
   cont = false; // or just break
 }
}
```
I hope this helps.

